     <td style=\"padding:5px 8px;color:#374151;line-height:1.5;\"><strong>Combined cap math:</strong> CAPR $308.48 = 40.7% of $758.71 portfolio. Only $70.87 headroom left under the 50% combined catalyst cap &#8212; not enough for any actionable new name.</td>\n    </tr>\n    <tr>\n      <td style=\"padding:5px 0;vertical-align:top;color:#64748b;\">&#8594;</td>\n      <td style=\"padding:5px 8px;color:#374151;line-height:1.5;\"><strong>Cash is optionality:</strong> CAPR positive AdCom (+30&#8211;80%) &#8594; cash becomes dry powder to ride PDUFA Aug 22 drift. CAPR negative AdCom &#8594; cash lets you rotate immediately into AMD (Aug 4) or LLY (Aug 5).</td>\n    </tr>\n    <tr>\n      <td style=\"padding:5px 0;vertical-align:top;color:#64748b;\">&#8594;</td>\n      <td style=\"padding:5px 8px;color:#374151;line-height:1.5;\"><strong>Anti-rotation rules:</strong> Buffett Indicator 236% = market at all-time expensive. Deploying $450 into a speculative new position at max valuation requires compelling asymmetry that doesn't exist right now with only $70 of cap headroom.</td>\n    </tr>\n    <tr>\n      <td style=\"padding:5px 0;vertical-align:top;color:#64748b;\">&#8594;</td>\n      <td style=\"padding:5px 8px;color:#374151;line-height:1.5;\"><strong>Free signal incoming:</strong> MNKD PDUFA July 26 (5 days). Watch its reaction &#8212; approval = FDA is running hot this cycle, positive read-through for CAPR AdCom July 29.</td>\n    </tr>\n  </table>\n\n  <div style=\"margin-top:12px;padding:10px 12px;background:#eff6ff;border-radius:6px;border-left:3px solid #3b82f6;font-size:12px;color:#1d4ed8;\">\n    <strong>Post-CAPR rotation shortlist:</strong> AMD (Aug 4, highest implied move 8&#8211;12%), LLY (Aug 5, GLP-1 strongest secular trend in pharma), TENX (August, if date confirmed). All halal clean.\n  </div>\n</div>\n\n<!-- EDUCATION CONCEPT #30 -->\n<div style=\"padding:16px 24px;border-bottom:1px solid #f1f5f9;\">\n  <div style=\"font-size:11px;color:#94a3b8;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:0.1em;font-weight:700;margin-bottom:4px;\">CONCEPT #30 OF 30 &#8212; CURRICULUM COMPLETE</div>\n  <div style=\"font-size:17px;font-weight:700;color:#1e293b;margin-bottom:12px;\">Sector Rotation Part 2: ETF Flows as a Real-Time Signal</div>\n\n  <p style=\"margin:0 0 10px;font-size:13px;color:#374151;line-height:1.6;\">Yesterday (July 20) you saw it live: Iran launched airstrikes and within hours <strong>XLV (healthcare) outperformed XLK (tech) by ~1.2% on the day.</strong> That's sector rotation &#8212; institutional money moving from growth to defensive sectors in real time. ETF flows are how you track it before the news cycle explains it.</p>\n\n  <div style=\"background:#fff;border:1px solid #e2e8f0;border-radius:8px;padding:14px;margin-bottom:12px;\">\n    <div style=\"font-size:13px;font-weight:700;color:#1e293b;margin-bottom:10px;\">The 3 ETF pairs to watch daily:</div>\n    <table style=\"border-collapse:collapse;width:100%;font-size:12px;\">\n      <tr style=\"border-bottom:1px solid #f1f5f9;\">\n        <td style=\"padding:7px 0;font-weight:700;color:#1e293b;width:100px;\">XLK vs XLV</td>\n        <td style=\"padding:7px 8px;color:#374151;\">Tech vs Healthcare. XLK leads in risk-on (AI spending up, VIX low). XLV leads in risk-off (geopolitical stress, recession fears). Yesterday: XLV led &#8212; Iran airstrike risk-off rotation.</td>\n      </tr>\n      <tr style=\"border-bottom:1px solid #f1f5f9;\">\n        <td style=\"padding:7px 0;font-weight:700;color:#1e293b;\">XLE vs XLU</td>\n        <td style=\"padding:7px 8px;color:#374151;\">Energy vs Utilities. XLE leads when oil spikes (Middle East events). XLU leads when rates fall and investors hunt yield.</td>\n      </tr>\n      <tr>\n        <td style=\"padding:7px 0;font-weight:700;color:#1e293b;\">IWM vs SPY</td>\n        <td style=\"padding:7px 8px;color:#374151;\">Small-cap vs Large-cap. IWM outperforming = high small-cap risk appetite &#8212; better environment for your CAPR-type catalyst plays. Watch this ratio before entering any new small-cap name.</td>\n      </tr>\n    </table>\n  </div>\n\n  <p style=\"margin:0 0 10px;font-size:13px;color:#374151;line-height:1.6;\"><strong>How to use it before entries:</strong> Before sizing into a catalyst play, check XLK/XLV ratio direction. If XLV is rising (risk-off), biotech names face a sector headwind even when the underlying catalyst is strong. If IWM is outperforming SPY, small-cap risk appetite is elevated &#8212; your catalyst plays run with the tide.</p>\n\n  <div style=\"padding:10px 14px;background:#dbeafe;border-radius:6px;border-left:3px solid #3b82f6;margin-bottom:10px;\">\n    <strong style=\"color:#1d4ed8;font-size:12px;\">Real example from yesterday:</strong> <span style=\"font-size:12px;color:#1e3a8a;\">Iran airstrikes &#8594; XLV outperformed XLK by ~1.2%. A trader watching the XLK/XLV ratio in real time would have seen the risk-off rotation 30 minutes before headlines explained it &#8212; and known that new tech speculative entries were a worse bet than healthcare defensive positions that day.</span>\n  </div>\n\n  <div style=\"padding:10px 14px;background:#f0fdf4;border-radius:6px;border-left:3px solid #059669;\">\n    <span style=\"font-size:13px;color:#166534;font-weight:600;\">&#127891; 30-concept curriculum complete.</span><span style=\"font-size:13px;color:#166534;\"> You've covered forward P/E, options, FDA calendars, short squeezes, sector rotation, hyperscaler capex, and 24 more foundational concepts over 30 trading days. The education section closes here &#8212; these concepts will appear going forward as applied analysis, not daily lessons. Well done.</span>\n  </div>\n</div>\n\n<!-- FOOTER -->\n<div style=\"padding:16px 24px;background:#1e293b;text-align:center;\">\n  <div style=\"font-size:12px;color:#64748b;margin-bottom:4px;\">Abbas Al Madani &middot; Portfolio Skills Daily &middot; Kuwait UTC+3</div>\n  <div style=\"font-size:11px;color:#475569;margin-bot